    • Method Detail

      • getPreOrderIterator

        <T> java.util.Iterator<T> getPreOrderIterator​(BinaryTreeNode<T> root)

        Creates a new Iterator that traverses the specified BinaryTreeNode in pre-order.

        The remove method of the returned Iterator is not supported and any call to it will result in an UnsupportedOperationException.

        This method is guaranteed to return in O(1) time. That is, it should not compute the entire order of traversal ahead of time.

        If the data in the underlying BinaryTreeNode or its children is modified, using the Iterator is unknown.

        Parameters:
        root - the root BinaryTreeNode to use for this Iterator
        Returns:
        a new Iterator that traverses the specified BinaryTreeNode in pre-order.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if root is null

      • getDepth

        <T> int getDepth​(BinaryTreeNode<T> root)

        Given a BinaryTreeNode computes the maximum distance that can be traveled from root to some child BinaryTreeNode. For example: 

         noChildren ->  A
 
 getDepth(noChildren); // returns 0
 
         someChildren ->  A
                /   \ 
               B     C <- depth 1
                    / 
                   D   <- depth 2
                  / \
                 E   F <- depth 3
                 
 getDepth(someChildren); // returns 3
        Parameters:
        root - the root BinaryTreeNode to examine
        Returns:
        the maximum distance that can be traveled from root
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if root is null

      • isBalanced

        <T> boolean isBalanced​(BinaryTreeNode<T> root,
                       int tolerance)
        A binary tree is said to be balanced if for each node in the tree the depth of each nodes children differs by at most some tolerance. Given a BinaryTreeNode and a tolerance, returns true if root is balanced and false otherwise.
        Parameters:
        root - the root BinaryTreeNode to examine
        int - the maximum tolerance to decide if the tree is balanced
        Returns:
        true if root is balanced and false otherwise.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if root is null
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if tolerance is less than 0

      • isBST

        <T extends java.lang.Comparable<? super T>> boolean isBST​(BinaryTreeNode<T> root)

        A BinaryTreeNode is said to be a Binary Search Tree if all of the following properties are true:

      • The left subtree of a node contains only nodes with values less than or equal to the value stored in root.
      • The right subtree of a node contains only nodes with values that are greater than the value stored in root.
      • The left and right subtree each must also be a binary search tree.

        • Given a BinaryTreeNode, returns true if root is a Binary Search Tree and false otherwise.

Parameters:
root - the BinaryTreeNode to examine
Returns:
true if root is a Binary Search Tree and false otherwise.
Throws:
java.lang.NullPointerException - if root is null
